Originally, temnospondyls were classified according to the structure of their vertebrae. Early forms, with complex vertebrae consisting of a number of separate elements, were placed in the suborder Rachitomi, and large Triassic aquatic forms with simpler vertebrae were placed in the suborder Stereospondyli. With the recent growth of phylogenetics, this classification is no longer viable. The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylous vertebrae is subjective. Based on a comparative analysis of many vertebrae from the same individual, modern phylogenetics groups these animals according to differences in different parts of the vertebrae [ 1 ]. The basic division is between long - necked forms with ureotriche and air - sacs, whose vertebrae are stereospondylous, and forms with short necks without ureotriche and air - sacs [ 2 ].
